1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:08,716
You do it constantly. You tap "I agree." You do
not read it — almost no one does . And buried in

2
00:00:08,716 --> 00:00:16,244
that fine print, again and again, is a single
clause that can quietly take away two of your most

3
00:00:16,244 --> 00:00:23,771
basic legal rights: the right to take the company
to court, and the right to join with everyone else

4
00:00:23,771 --> 00:00:31,299
they treated the same way . In 2011, a fight over
about thirty dollars turned that clause into the

5
00:00:31,299 --> 00:00:33,280
law of the land .

6
00:00:33,672 --> 00:00:42,001
The clause is an arbitration agreement. It says
that if you have a dispute, you will not sue in a

7
00:00:42,001 --> 00:00:49,913
public court — you will take it to a private
arbitrator, one customer at a time. And it usually

8
00:00:49,913 --> 00:00:56,576
adds a second piece: a class-action waiver, a
promise that you will never band together with

9
00:00:56,576 --> 00:01:04,072
other people who were harmed the same way . This
is one of the most consequential and most

10
00:01:04,072 --> 00:01:09,485
argued-about features of modern American law, and
reasonable people strongly disagree about whether

11
00:01:09,485 --> 00:01:16,148
it is fair. Over the next twelve minutes: the
thirty-dollar case that made it enforceable, what

12
00:01:16,148 --> 00:01:20,729
the Court actually decided, and the honest
arguments on both sides.

13
00:01:21,121 --> 00:01:29,199
It starts with a couple in California, Vincent and
Liza Concepcion. They sign up with AT&T for

14
00:01:29,199 --> 00:01:36,327
cellphones advertised as "free." Then the bill
comes, and they have been charged about thirty

15
00:01:36,327 --> 00:01:40,604
dollars in sales tax on those "free" phones .

16
00:01:40,997 --> 00:01:48,668
Thirty dollars. On its own, it is nothing — no
lawyer on earth takes a thirty-dollar case. And

17
00:01:48,668 --> 00:01:55,913
that is exactly the point that makes this story
matter. Because the Concepcions were not the only

18
00:01:55,913 --> 00:02:03,584
customer charged that tax. If a company charges
thirty dollars too much to one person, it is a

19
00:02:03,584 --> 00:02:11,255
rounding error. If it charges thirty dollars too
much to millions of people, it is tens of millions

20
00:02:11,255 --> 00:02:15,517
of dollars — and now it is worth fighting .

21
00:02:15,909 --> 00:02:23,101
The tool for that fight is the class action: a
single lawsuit that bundles together everyone with

22
00:02:23,101 --> 00:02:30,717
the same small claim, so that harms too tiny to
sue over individually can be challenged all at

23
00:02:30,717 --> 00:02:34,101
once. The Concepcions wanted to bring one .

24
00:02:34,494 --> 00:02:43,173
But their AT&T contract said no. It required any
dispute to go to individual arbitration, and it

25
00:02:43,173 --> 00:02:50,320
specifically waived class actions . So the legal
question became: is that waiver enforceable?

26
00:02:50,320 --> 00:02:58,489
California had a rule — from a case called
Discover Bank — that treated these class-action

27
00:02:58,489 --> 00:03:05,636
waivers in consumer contracts as unconscionable,
and refused to enforce them. Under California law,

28
00:03:05,636 --> 00:03:09,720
the Concepcions could keep their class action .

29
00:03:10,113 --> 00:03:17,662
AT&T argued that California rule had to give way
to a much older federal law. And so a dispute over

30
00:03:17,662 --> 00:03:24,833
thirty dollars in phone tax became a case about
who gets to decide whether you can ever join a

31
00:03:24,833 --> 00:03:26,342
class action at all.

32
00:03:26,735 --> 00:03:37,362
To understand the case, you have to understand two
things: a 1925 law, and one small, powerful

33
00:03:37,362 --> 00:03:37,987
sentence.

34
00:03:38,380 --> 00:03:45,890
The 1925 law is the Federal Arbitration Act. It
was passed to make arbitration agreements

35
00:03:45,890 --> 00:03:53,400
enforceable, reflecting a federal policy that
favors arbitration — the idea that if two parties

36
00:03:53,400 --> 00:04:02,913
agree to resolve disputes privately, courts should
hold them to it . For most of its life, that law

37
00:04:02,913 --> 00:04:08,921
lived quietly. Then companies began writing
arbitration clauses into the everyday contracts

38
00:04:08,921 --> 00:04:14,930
ordinary people sign — for phones, banks, credit
cards, and jobs .

39
00:04:15,322 --> 00:04:23,795
And here is what makes them so easy to miss. You
do not sign these clauses with a pen at a desk.

40
00:04:23,795 --> 00:04:30,728
You accept them by activating a phone, opening an
account, clicking a box, or showing up for your

41
00:04:30,728 --> 00:04:38,816
first day of work. The law treats that as a real
agreement — and for the most part, the terms are

42
00:04:38,816 --> 00:04:46,133
not up for negotiation. It is take it or leave it,
and "leaving it" can mean going without the

43
00:04:46,133 --> 00:04:48,059
service, or the job .

44
00:04:48,452 --> 00:04:55,420
The powerful sentence is the class-action waiver.
Arbitration by itself just changes the venue —

45
00:04:55,420 --> 00:05:02,852
court versus a private arbitrator. The waiver does
something more: it forces every claim to be

46
00:05:02,852 --> 00:05:11,214
brought one person at a time. And for the small,
scattered harms we just described, "one person at

47
00:05:11,214 --> 00:05:19,575
a time" can mean, in practice, "no one at all,"
because no individual claim is large enough to

48
00:05:19,575 --> 00:05:20,504
pursue .

49
00:05:20,897 --> 00:05:28,993
This is where honest people split, and it is worth
hearing both sides plainly. Critics argue that

50
00:05:28,993 --> 00:05:35,660
mandatory arbitration with class-action waivers —
what they call "forced arbitration" — can quietly

51
00:05:35,660 --> 00:05:42,328
close the courthouse door, leaving widespread
small harms with no realistic remedy, decided in

52
00:05:42,328 --> 00:05:46,138
private proceedings that set no public precedent .

53
00:05:46,530 --> 00:05:53,409
Defenders argue the opposite: that arbitration is
generally faster, cheaper, and less formal than a

54
00:05:53,409 --> 00:05:59,371
lawsuit, that the 1925 law reflects a
long-standing policy of honoring agreements people

55
00:05:59,371 --> 00:06:07,625
make, and that individual claimants can sometimes
do as well or better than they would in a crowded

56
00:06:07,625 --> 00:06:14,962
court . Those empirical claims — about cost,
speed, and outcomes — are genuinely disputed, and

57
00:06:14,962 --> 00:06:22,758
we are not going to pretend one side has settled
them. The case is about who decides.

58
00:06:23,151 --> 00:06:33,156
In 2011, the Supreme Court sided with AT&T. By a
vote of five to four, it held that the Federal

59
00:06:33,156 --> 00:06:40,659
Arbitration Act preempts California's rule — that
a state cannot refuse to enforce a class-action

60
00:06:40,659 --> 00:06:47,662
waiver just because it finds the waiver unfair. If
the contract says individual arbitration,

61
00:06:47,662 --> 00:06:50,164
individual arbitration it is .

62
00:06:50,556 --> 00:06:58,315
The opinion was written by Justice Antonin Scalia.
A state rule that singles out arbitration's

63
00:06:58,315 --> 00:07:06,074
class-action waivers and blocks them, he reasoned,
stands as an obstacle to the federal policy

64
00:07:06,074 --> 00:07:12,281
favoring arbitration, and so it cannot stand. The
federal law wins .

65
00:07:12,673 --> 00:07:19,776
Justice Stephen Breyer wrote the dissent, and it
put the other half of the problem into words. For

66
00:07:19,776 --> 00:07:26,879
claims worth only a few dollars each, he argued,
the class action is often the only realistic way

67
00:07:26,879 --> 00:07:34,770
to hold a large company accountable at all. Take
it away, and you have not just changed the forum —

68
00:07:34,770 --> 00:07:38,716
you may have ended the case before it starts .

69
00:07:39,109 --> 00:07:46,747
That five-to-four split did not settle the
country's mind, but it settled the law. And seven

70
00:07:46,747 --> 00:07:55,341
years later, the Court extended it into the one
place most adults spend their days: work. In Epic

71
00:07:55,341 --> 00:08:02,980
Systems v. Lewis, in 2018, by another five-to-four
vote, with Justice Neil Gorsuch writing, the Court

72
00:08:02,980 --> 00:08:09,664
held that employers, too, can require employees to
arbitrate individually and waive class or

73
00:08:09,664 --> 00:08:18,258
collective actions — and that doing so does not
violate federal labor law . The same logic that

74
00:08:18,258 --> 00:08:22,077
governed your phone contract now governed your
job.

75
00:08:22,470 --> 00:08:28,944
Epic was not a quiet decision either. Justice Ruth
Bader Ginsburg wrote a forceful dissent, arguing

76
00:08:28,944 --> 00:08:36,229
that forcing employees to face their employer one
at a time ignored the very reason federal law lets

77
00:08:36,229 --> 00:08:43,918
workers act together — and she read part of it
aloud from the bench, a step justices reserve for

78
00:08:43,918 --> 00:08:46,750
the rulings they most strongly oppose .

79
00:08:47,143 --> 00:08:53,097
So here is where it leaves you. Mandatory
arbitration clauses, with class-action waivers,

80
00:08:53,097 --> 00:09:01,341
are now a standard feature of American life — in
the contracts for your phone, your bank account,

81
00:09:01,341 --> 00:09:08,211
your streaming apps, and very often your
employment . You have almost certainly agreed to

82
00:09:08,211 --> 00:09:15,081
several of them, by doing nothing more than using
a service or starting a job.

83
00:09:15,473 --> 00:09:22,511
Whether that is a good thing depends on which
argument you find more convincing, and that is a

84
00:09:22,511 --> 00:09:30,331
real debate, not a settled one . What is not in
dispute is the mechanism. Two ordinary rights — to

85
00:09:30,331 --> 00:09:37,759
sue in open court, and to join with others — are
now, for most people, waivable by a sentence

86
00:09:37,759 --> 00:09:39,323
almost no one reads.

87
00:09:39,716 --> 00:09:48,534
What can you actually do about it? Honestly, not
much in the moment — the terms are rarely

88
00:09:48,534 --> 00:09:55,392
negotiable. But the argument itself is not over.
Lawmakers, regulators, and companies keep fighting

89
00:09:55,392 --> 00:10:02,740
over where mandatory arbitration should apply and
where it should not, especially for the most

90
00:10:02,740 --> 00:10:11,068
serious kinds of claims. The line this series
keeps chasing is, here too, still being drawn .

91
00:10:11,460 --> 00:10:18,601
And notice what makes this different from
everything else in this series. No officer took

92
00:10:18,601 --> 00:10:25,742
anything. No school punished anyone. The power
here was handed over voluntarily, in the most

93
00:10:25,742 --> 00:10:32,407
ordinary act of modern life: tapping a button to
make a screen go away.

94
00:10:32,799 --> 00:10:39,176
A thirty-dollar charge on a "free" phone ended up
drawing one of the quietest but widest lines in

95
00:10:39,176 --> 00:10:45,907
modern law — the line between the rights you have
and the rights you can sign away without realizing

96
00:10:45,907 --> 00:10:53,700
it . The Court did not take those rights from you.
It said you were free to give them up. The fine

97
00:10:53,700 --> 00:10:55,117
print did the rest.

98
00:10:55,510 --> 00:11:03,518
We have now watched the state search you, track
you, take your property, and police your speech —

99
00:11:03,518 --> 00:11:10,636
and watched you hand over rights yourself, by
contract. In every case, the same question keeps

100
00:11:10,636 --> 00:11:17,309
returning in a new costume: where is the line, and
who gets to move it?

101
00:11:17,701 --> 00:11:25,242
The next case moves that question somewhere more
intimate than a phone or a contract. Not what you

102
00:11:25,242 --> 00:11:33,201
carry, or what you sign, but what is inside your
body. When the police arrest you — before any

103
00:11:33,201 --> 00:11:41,160
trial, before any conviction — can they take a
sample of your DNA, and keep it? That is next

104
00:11:41,160 --> 00:11:41,579
time.
